record_exploration_finding
{
  "path": "crates/nyx-agent/src/main.rs",
  "line": 840,
  "cap": "OS_COMMAND",
  "endpoint": "<cli:--open-cmd>",
  "rationale": "The --open-cmd <cmd> flag is fed straight to std::process::Command::new(&cmd).arg(&url_for_open). No allowlist. Command::new bypasses the shell, so URL metacharacters do not inject; however the cmd value itself is taken verbatim from the CLI, so any caller that builds the daemon invocation from semi-trusted state (orchestration script reading env, supervisord with config drift, etc.) is one substitution away from arbitrary binary spawn at startup. Low severity in isolation, but pairs cleanly with the pre-setup auth-bypass finding: an attacker who reaches the wizard could plant a remediation hint pointing the operator at `--open-cmd /tmp/payload`. Static pass missed because Command::new() with a literal-looking variable does not match the canonical OS-injection sink shape (no shell, no format!).",
  "suggested_payload_hint": "n/a — defence is a positive allowlist for --open-cmd (xdg-open, open, start) or drop the flag on production builds."
}
